## ð Article 4 â TDM for Commercial Use (With Opt-Out)

### Scope

**PERMITTED** text and data mining for **any purpose**, including commercial, where:

- The beneficiary has **lawful access** to the content
- The rightsholder has **NOT expressly reserved** (opted out) their rights

### The Opt-Out Right (Critical)

**Art. 4(3)** â Rightsholders may **expressly reserve** their rights against TDM, including AI processing. When they do:

- The Art. 4 exception **no longer applies**
- Processing the content with AI/LLM **constitutes copyright infringement**
- The reservation must be expressed in a **machine-readable format** for online content
- For physical/offline documents: any clear textual statement constitutes a valid opt-out

### ðŦ Prohibited Actions When Opt-Out Is Detected

- **NEVER** pass document text to an LLM after detecting a valid opt-out
- **NEVER** index or embed the document in a vector database
- **NEVER** use the document as RAG context
- **NEVER** extract rules, plans, or assumptions from the document using AI
- **NEVER** store extracted information derived from an opted-out document

---

## ð AI Opt-Out Pattern Detection

### Mandatory Scan Zones

Always scan at minimum the **first 3,000 characters** of a document (headers, copyright notices, preambles). Also scan common positions:

- Page 1 header/footer
- Document metadata (`<dc:rights>`, PDF metadata fields)
- Last page legal notices
- Appendices titled "Legal notices", "Copyright", "Terms of use"
- robots.txt for online sources
- HTML meta tags: `<meta name="robots" content="noai,noimageai">`

